\operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x] has a unique non-standard open subscheme, which we denote as \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x]_+ = \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x]-\{ ot \}, where  ot is the generic point of \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x]. The open subscheme \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x]_+ is not compact, hence it is not affine. However, \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {H}[x]_+ can be seen as arising from a more general construction on image finite posets, see Example .

Let \mathbb {S}[x] be the free coHeyting algebra with one generator. By duality, since free distributive lattices are self-dual 2[x]^{\mathrm {op}} \cong 2[x], we in fact have \mathbb {S}[x] \cong \mathbb {H}[x]^{\mathrm {op}}, where \mathbb {H}[x] is the Rieger-Nishimura algebra. This way, we can compute \mathbb {S}[x] and \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {S}[x] as below,
\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver} \begin {tikzcd} & {\mathbb {S}[x]} & {\mathrm {Spec}\,\mathbb {S}[x]} \\ 1 &&& \top \\ {1\backslash x} & x & \vdots & \vdots \\ {x \wedge (1\backslash x)} & {1\backslash (1\backslash x)} & \bullet & \bullet \\ {x\backslash (1\backslash (1\backslash x))} & {1\backslash x \wedge 1\backslash (1\backslash x)} & \bullet & \bullet \\ \vdots & \vdots & \bullet & \bullet \\ & 0 & \bullet & \bullet \arrow [from=3-1, to=2-1] \arrow [from=3-2, to=2-1] \arrow [from=3-3, to=2-4] \arrow [from=3-4, to=2-4] \arrow [from=4-1, to=3-1] \arrow [from=4-1, to=3-2] \arrow [from=4-2, to=3-2] \arrow [from=4-3, to=3-3] \arrow [from=4-3, to=3-4] \arrow [from=4-4, to=3-4] \arrow [from=5-1, to=4-1] \arrow [from=5-2, to=4-1] \arrow [from=5-2, to=4-2] \arrow [from=5-3, to=4-3] \arrow [from=5-3, to=4-4] \arrow [from=5-4, to=3-3] \arrow [from=5-4, to=4-4] \arrow [from=6-1, to=5-1] \arrow [from=6-1, to=5-2] \arrow [from=6-2, to=5-2] \arrow [from=6-3, to=5-3] \arrow [from=6-3, to=5-4] \arrow [from=6-4, to=4-3] \arrow [from=6-4, to=5-4] \arrow [from=7-2, to=6-1] \arrow [from=7-2, to=6-2] \arrow [from=7-3, to=6-3] \arrow [from=7-3, to=6-4] \arrow [from=7-4, to=5-3] \arrow [from=7-4, to=6-4] \end {tikzcd}
\operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {S}[x] is the union of two standard opens \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {S}[x] = \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {S}[x]/ x \cup \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {S}[x]/ (1\backslash x) However, the interesting thing here is that their intersection is isomorphic to the total space again \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {S}[x]/x \cap \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {S}[x]/(1\backslash x) = \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {S}[x]/(x \wedge (1\backslash x)) \cong \operatorname {Spec}\mathbb {S}[x]. This seems to hint at a coinductive feature of \mathbb {S}[x].

  For a class of maps between schemes, we say it is affine admissible, if 

It is closed under compositions and pullbacks;

It is affine local on the target.

Let A be local, and X a scheme. A map f : \operatorname {Spec} A \to  X always factors through the inclusion \operatorname {Spec}{\mathcal {O}_{X,x}} \to  X specified in Lemma , where x = f(\bot ) for the root in \operatorname {Spec} A,

\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}
  \begin {tikzcd}
    {\mathrm {Spec}\,A} & {\mathrm {Spec}\,\mathcal  O_{X,x}} \\
    & X
    \arrow [dashed, from=1-1, to=1-2]
    \arrow ["f"', from=1-1, to=2-2]
    \arrow [from=1-2, to=2-2]
  \end {tikzcd}


In particular, \operatorname {Spec} A \to  \operatorname {Spec}\mathcal {O}_{X,x} preserves the root, or in other words \mathcal {O}_{X,x} \to  A is t-conservative. This means a map \operatorname {Spec} A \to  X can be identified as a pair (x,f) where x\in  X is a point, and f : \mathcal {O}_{X,x} \to  A is a t-conservative map.

If we now start from a closed set Y, for any x\in X we have
 egin {align*} x\in C_{\mathcal {I}_Y} &\Leftrightarrow 1 
ot \in \mathcal {I}_{Y,x} \ &\Leftrightarrow  orall U	ext {open}
i x.\, 1 
ot \in \mathcal {I}_Y(U) \ &\Leftrightarrow  orall U	ext {open}
i x.\, Y \cap U 
eq \emptyset \ &\Leftrightarrow x \in Y \end {align*}
The third equivalence holds since by construction, 1 \in \mathcal {I}_Y(U) \Leftrightarrow  orall y \in Y \cap U.\ y 
ot \models 1 \Leftrightarrow Y \cap U = \emptyset . The final equivalence holds since Y is closed.

Let X be a scheme, and \mathcal {I} an ideal of \mathcal {O}_{X}. \mathcal {I} is quasi-coherent iff for all affine open \operatorname {Spec} A of X and a\in  A, the canonical factorisation

\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}
  \begin {tikzcd}
    {\mathcal  I(\mathrm {Spec} A)} \\
    {a \wedge  \mathcal  I(\mathrm {Spec}A)} & {\mathcal  I(\mathrm {Spec}A/a)}
    \arrow [two heads, from=1-1, to=2-1]
    \arrow [from=1-1, to=2-2]
    \arrow [from=2-1, to=2-2]
  \end {tikzcd}


induces an equivalence a \wedge  \mathcal {I}(\operatorname {Spec} A) = \mathcal {I}(\operatorname {Spec} A/a).
